What is type inference in Go?

Type inference in Go means the Go compiler automatically determines the type of a 
variable based on the value you assign to it â€” without you explicitly specifying the type.

Example of Type Inference
name := "Mahindra"  // inferred as string
age := 30           // inferred as int
price := 99.99      // inferred as float64
flag := true        // inferred as bool
Here, := is the short variable declaration operator. 
Go infers the type based on the assigned value.

 Concept                        Description                                           
 âœ… Automatically typed          Compiler assigns the correct type from the value      
 ğŸ› ï¸ Requires initialization      You must assign a value when using type inference 
 âŒ Only works inside functions  Outside functions (e.g., global scope), use `var`     

ğŸ§  Behind the Scenes
When you write:
            count := 10
The Go compiler internally treats it as:
          var count int = 10
